terior (lambda)","Frontal"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior (lambda)\u003C/strong\u003E fontanelle is expected to close by 2-3 months of age. This is the first fontanelle to close in infants. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior (bregma)\u003C/strong\u003E fontanelle closes much later, between 12-18 months. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid (pterion)\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emastoid (asterion)\u003C/strong\u003E fontanelles close around 6 months of age. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal\u003C/strong\u003E fontanelle is not a standard term used for fontanelles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior fontanelle, also known as the lambda, closes by 2-3 months of age.","The anterior fontanelle, or bregma, usually closes between 12-18 months of age.","The sphenoid and mastoid fontanelles close around 6 months of age."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64015"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17953"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64015"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:07:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:08:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10667"}},"content":{"data":{"type"